            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How to interpret the HAS-BLED score</h2>
              <p>
                The HAS-BLED score was developed to estimate the 1‑year risk of
                major bleeding in patients with atrial fibrillation (AF) on oral
                anticoagulation. It assigns 1 point for each risk factor, for a
                maximum of 9 points.
              </p>

              <div class="overflow-x-auto my-4">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Score</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">
                        Risk category
                      </th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">
                        Approximate annual major bleeding risk*
                      </th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">
                        Suggested action
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-b">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">0–1</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">Low</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~1% per year</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Standard follow‑up; address any modifiable factors.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-b bg-gray-50">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">2</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">Moderate</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">~2% per year</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Review blood pressure, concomitant drugs, alcohol, and
                        renal/liver function.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">≥ 3</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">High</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        ≥ 3–5% per year (varies by cohort)
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Consider more frequent review, correction of reversible
                        risk factors, and careful selection/monitoring of
                        anticoagulant.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                *Approximate risks based on original and subsequent validation
                cohorts; actual risk depends on patient population and
                anticoagulant used.
              </p>

              <h2>Components of the HAS-BLED score</h2>
              <p>The acronym <strong>HAS-BLED</strong> stands for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>H – Hypertension:</strong> Uncontrolled systolic blood
                  pressure &gt; 160 mmHg.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>A – Abnormal renal and/or liver function:</strong> 1
                  point each (maximum 2 points).
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <em>Renal:</em> Dialysis, transplant, or creatinine ≥ 200
                      µmol/L (≈ 2.26 mg/dL).
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Liver:</em> Cirrhosis or bilirubin &gt; 2× normal plus
                      AST/ALT/AP &gt; 3× normal.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>S – Stroke:</strong> Previous ischemic or hemorrhagic
                  stroke.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>B – Bleeding:</strong> Prior major bleeding
                  (especially intracranial) or bleeding predisposition (e.g.,
                  anemia).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>L – Labile INR:</strong> Time in therapeutic range
                  (TTR) &lt; 60% in patients on warfarin/VKA.
                </li>
                <li><strong>E – Elderly:</strong> Age &gt; 65 years.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>D – Drugs or alcohol:</strong> 1 point each (maximum 2
                  points).
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <em>Drugs:</em> Concomitant antiplatelets or NSAIDs.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Alcohol:</em> Excess intake (e.g., ≥ 8 drinks/week or
                      clinician‑defined).
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>HAS-BLED total score</strong> =</p>
                <p>
                  H (0–1) + A<sub>renal</sub> (0–1) + A<sub>liver</sub> (0–1) +
                  S (0–1) + B (0–1) + L (0–1) + E (0–1) + D<sub>drugs</sub>
                  (0–1) + D<sub>alcohol</sub> (0–1)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-gray-500">
                  Minimum 0, maximum 9 points.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Clinical use and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Purpose:</strong> To flag patients at higher bleeding
                  risk and highlight modifiable risk factors.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Not a stand‑alone decision tool:</strong> A high
                  HAS-BLED score should not automatically preclude
                  anticoagulation; instead, it should prompt risk mitigation and
                  closer follow‑up.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use with stroke risk scores:</strong> Typically used
                  alongside CHA<sub>2</sub>DS<sub>2</sub>-VASc to balance stroke
                  prevention benefit vs bleeding risk.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Population:</strong> Developed in AF patients on
                  vitamin K antagonists; widely applied to DOAC‑treated
                  patients, though absolute risks may differ.
                </li>
              </ul>

