            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Should I score labile INR in patients on DOACs?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The labile INR component applies to patients on vitamin K
                antagonists (e.g., warfarin). For patients on DOACs who have
                never been on warfarin, this component is usually scored as 0.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I reassess the HAS-BLED score?</h3>
              <p>
                Reassessment is reasonable whenever there is a significant
                change in clinical status (e.g., new renal or liver dysfunction,
                new antiplatelet therapy, major bleeding event) and at least
                annually in patients on long‑term anticoagulation.
              </p>

              <h3>What modifiable bleeding risk factors can I address?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Optimize blood pressure control.</li>
                <li>
                  Review and minimize concomitant antiplatelets and NSAIDs where
                  possible.
                </li>
                <li>Address excess alcohol intake.</li>
                <li>Monitor and manage renal and liver function.</li>
                <li>
                  For warfarin users, improve TTR (e.g., dosing review,
                  adherence support) or consider switching to a DOAC where
                  appropriate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Is HAS-BLED validated outside atrial fibrillation?</h3>
              <p>
                The score was developed and validated primarily in atrial
                fibrillation cohorts. While sometimes extrapolated to other
                anticoagulated populations, its performance may differ and
                should be interpreted cautiously outside AF.
              </p>
